      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As the headline to Jared Diamond's Jan. 8 Op-Ed article says, there has been a ''Greening of Corporate America.'' The evidence abounds, including the growing number of mutual funds that invest in companies that get high marks on environmental matters.</p>
        <p>The movement is not confined to Western economies. The aggressive business response to international environmental standards in the export-oriented economies of Malaysia, Singapore, South Korea and Taiwan reflects the growing environmental discipline of the global marketplace. Indeed, given the global spread of corporate environmentalism, we have reason to anticipate what may come to be called a ''clean revolution'' in the first century of the new millennium.</p>
        <p>OWEN CYLKE  Washington, Jan. 11, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is coordinator of the Policy Group, U.S.-Asia Environmental Partnership.</p>
      </block>
